00:00:20.380 --> 00:00:22.000
Welcome back, everyone.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.350
We are going to start session
five, the last session of the day.

00:00:26.350 --> 00:00:30.460
This session is on
permanent exemptions.

00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:32.480
And I'll just read the description.

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:35.650 position:56%
This session will explore the
necessity, relevance and sufficiency

00:00:35.650 --> 00:00:38.880
of the permanent exemptions to
the prohibition on circumvention

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:41.000 position:56%
and will consider whether amendments

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.650
or additional exemption
categories may be advisable.

00:00:44.650 --> 00:00:48.580
So to get started, I'd just like
to ask the panelists once again

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:53.350
to introduce themselves and
along with their affiliation.

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:55.250
&gt;&gt; June M. Besek: June Besek,
Kernochan Center for Law,

00:00:55.250 --> 00:00:58.890
Media and the Arts at
Columbia Law School.

00:00:58.890 --> 00:01:01.170
&gt;&gt; Gabe Cazares: Gabe Cazares,
Government Affairs Specialist,

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:04.270
National Federation of the Blind.

00:01:04.270 --> 00:01:05.570
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: Krista Cox,

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:07.770
with the Association
of Research Libraries.

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:13.450
&gt;&gt; Troy Dow: Troy Dow, with
The Walt Disney Company.

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:15.500
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: Harley
Geiger, with Rapid7.

00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:17.130
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Matt Williams.

00:01:17.130 --> 00:01:22.800
I'm here on behalf of
AAP, MPAA and RIAA.

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:24.490
&gt;&gt; James Love: Jamie
Love, James Love,

00:01:24.490 --> 00:01:27.030
with Knowledge Ecology
International.

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:30.460
&gt;&gt; David Perry: David Perry,
with the law firm of Blank Rome,

00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:36.830
on behalf of Doorman Products, Inc.

00:01:36.830 --> 00:01:39.130
&gt;&gt; Chris Mohr: Chris Mohr, SIIA.

00:01:41.100 --> 00:01:43.880
&gt;&gt; Maryna Koberidze: Maryna
Koberidze, no affiliation.

00:01:43.880 --> 00:01:48.650
I'm here as a concerned member of
the public and IP law enthusiast.

00:01:48.650 --> 00:01:49.950
Thank you.

00:01:49.950 --> 00:01:53.870
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: And a
proud alum of our office.

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:56.220
So, welcome all.

00:01:56.220 --> 00:02:03.320
So I thought we would proceed sort
of in two parts, first by looking

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:06.790
at the adequacy and
the functionality

00:02:06.790 --> 00:02:12.500
of the current exemptions
and then turning to proposals

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:18.100
for additional permanent
exemptions and to get your thoughts

00:02:18.100 --> 00:02:21.360
on whether any may be
necessary or advisable.

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:25.020
We're thinking of proceeding
a little bit differently

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:26.590
in this session.

00:02:26.590 --> 00:02:31.710
As you know, a lot of the existing
permanent exemptions are specific

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:37.290
to particular types of uses and are
maybe more relevant to particular--

00:02:37.290 --> 00:02:39.330
to certain of you than others.

00:02:39.330 --> 00:02:45.170
So we may direct questions
specifically to individual people

00:02:45.170 --> 00:02:49.460
to start out with, but everyone
obviously is welcome to weigh in

00:02:49.460 --> 00:02:51.770
and in fact, we, you know,
we encourage you to do so.

00:02:51.770 --> 00:02:55.090
So I wanted to start by talking

00:02:55.090 --> 00:03:00.540
about the library exemption
under Section 1201(d).

00:03:00.540 --> 00:03:05.110
We received a number of
comments on this exemption

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:08.130
from library associations.

00:03:08.130 --> 00:03:14.090
I think the word useless came
up in one or two of them.

00:03:14.090 --> 00:03:17.310
And so, if I could direct
this to you, Ms. Cox,

00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:22.540 position:56%
I just would be interested just sort
of generally in your perspective

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:27.280
on the current library exemption,
you know, if you could sort

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:33.430
of elaborate on why it may
not be as useful as hoped,

00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:37.830
and any changes you
would like to see.

00:03:37.830 --> 00:03:39.370
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: Well,
I certainly think

00:03:39.370 --> 00:03:45.050
that Section 1201(d) is not very
useful for libraries, archives

00:03:45.050 --> 00:03:46.380
and educational institutions.

00:03:46.380 --> 00:03:49.060
It's not actually an
exemption that we asked

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:56.890 position:56%
for in the DMCA legislative hearings
and that whole process because it's

00:03:56.890 --> 00:04:00.190
so narrowly drafted,
it's not an exemption

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:02.860
for any nonprofit library
or educational use.

00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:06.840
It's not even an exemption for
any library or educational use

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:09.670
that is already granted
under, you know, Section 108

00:04:09.670 --> 00:04:11.180
or granted under fair use.

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:16.100
It's so narrowly tailored to
only acquisition decisions.

00:04:16.100 --> 00:04:19.980
And you can only use that
exemption for the time necessary

00:04:19.980 --> 00:04:21.600
for an acquisition decision.

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:26.140
And it is our view that if
we are going out and looking

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:31.220 position:56%
to make an acquisition, that whoever
is selling that book or that product

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:34.910
to us would be happy to open
up that digital lock for us

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:37.390
to make that determination.

00:04:37.390 --> 00:04:45.080 position:56%
We find that we are constantly using
every three years the rulemaking

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:49.690
process to pursue the exemptions
that we think are really necessary,

00:04:49.690 --> 00:04:54.650
for example, to-- for
assistive technologies for those

00:04:54.650 --> 00:04:59.090 position:56%
that are blind, visually impaired or
print-disabled, for educational uses

00:04:59.090 --> 00:05:01.100
of audiovisual materials.

00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:06.020
So for us, those are the types
of uses that we would find--

00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:10.680
that we need continually and that
would warrant a permanent exemption

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:14.740
versus the very narrow
exemption in 1201(d).

00:05:14.740 --> 00:05:16.040
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:20.410
And so, just sort of in practice,
I mean, in your experience,

00:05:20.410 --> 00:05:25.090
is the current exemption-- I mean,
it sounds like the answer is no.

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:27.940
Do you know of many examples

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:30.720
of librarians making
use of that exemption?

00:05:30.720 --> 00:05:33.250
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: I don't, because
I don't know of content providers

00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:37.160
who hand something over to
a library locked and say,

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:39.990
do you want this product,
it's locked.

00:05:39.990 --> 00:05:44.380
No, I mean, it just-- for
purposes of acquisitions,

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:47.470
normally the content providers
are happy to unlock it for us

00:05:47.470 --> 00:05:49.410 position:56%
as we make a decision in purchasing.

00:05:49.410 --> 00:05:50.710
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: OK.

00:05:50.710 --> 00:05:52.010
Now-- Oh, sorry.

00:05:52.010 --> 00:05:53.310
Go ahead.

00:05:53.310 --> 00:05:54.610
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Can I ask what are
your thoughts about reforming it

00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:58.260
to track the contours of 108
which is different, I will say,

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:01.450
than some of the petitions for
exemptions in the rulemaking.

00:06:01.450 --> 00:06:04.160
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: I think that--

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:10.540
I mean, I think that
there are certainly areas

00:06:10.540 --> 00:06:16.820
where it would be useful
to amend 1201 in order

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:19.920
to accommodate what's
allowed under 108.

00:06:19.920 --> 00:06:27.530
But there are, of course, other
uses as well that we would support.

00:06:27.530 --> 00:06:28.830
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Oh, sorry.

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:31.920
So-- Well yeah, so I think
that was one proposal.

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:35.590
I mean, I know in our comments
from the American Association

00:06:35.590 --> 00:06:38.650
of Law Libraries, there
was a recommendation

00:06:38.650 --> 00:06:43.650
that a permanent exemption
be created for any use

00:06:43.650 --> 00:06:47.080
that was permissible under 108.

00:06:47.080 --> 00:06:50.840
I assume-- Is that something
that you're recommending as well

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:54.280
or do you think that the,
you know, the exemptions

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:57.060
that you've petitioned
for pertaining

00:06:57.060 --> 00:07:01.970
to motion pictures are sort
of a more pressing concern?

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:04.980
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: Can we have both?

00:07:04.980 --> 00:07:06.650
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Well--

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:07.950
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: No.

00:07:07.950 --> 00:07:09.250
I mean, yes.

00:07:09.250 --> 00:07:12.090
I think that, you know, having--

00:07:12.090 --> 00:07:17.610
expanding it to apply to Section
108 would be very, very helpful.

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:21.440
And, you know, I think this just
highlights a fundamental flaw

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:23.880
of the 1201 process that,
you know, has been talked

00:07:23.880 --> 00:07:26.810
about in these roundtables, that
it's not linked to infringement.

00:07:26.810 --> 00:07:30.110
And it's, you know, from the
perspective of our libraries,

00:07:30.110 --> 00:07:35.530
who really do want to follow the
law and, you know, ensure that--

00:07:35.530 --> 00:07:38.260
simultaneously ensuring that
we are fulfilling our mission,

00:07:38.260 --> 00:07:42.170
that it doesn't really make sense
to have these exemptions granted

00:07:42.170 --> 00:07:44.930
under Section 108 or be
allowed under fair use.

00:07:44.930 --> 00:07:46.230
But then, you can't
actually do it just

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:47.850
because we've moved
into a digital world.

00:07:47.850 --> 00:07:51.510
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Are there
any other views on sort

00:07:51.510 --> 00:07:54.560
of the advisability
of-- oh, I'm sorry.

00:07:54.560 --> 00:07:56.010
I didn't even see.

00:07:56.010 --> 00:07:58.540
Mr. Williams?

00:08:00.510 --> 00:08:06.040
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:08:06.040 --> 00:08:07.340
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: We're mic-less.

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:08.640
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Oh,
mine just came on.

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:09.940
OK, great.

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:11.240
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: OK.

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:12.540
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Thank you.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:17.200
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Oh yeah, if we could
just ask if you're not speaking

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:19.170
to turn off your microphone?

00:08:19.170 --> 00:08:21.340
Thank you.

00:08:21.340 --> 00:08:22.730
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Thank you.

00:08:22.730 --> 00:08:26.990 position:56%
I did see that the library community
is not finding the existing

00:08:26.990 --> 00:08:28.400
exemption helpful.

00:08:28.400 --> 00:08:30.160
And it sounds to me like that's

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:32.620
because the market is
working really well.

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:35.710
As she said, copyright
owners are more than willing

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:40.490
to give test access to libraries
so that they can sample the works

00:08:40.490 --> 00:08:41.790
and decide whether to buy them.

00:08:41.790 --> 00:08:46.900
So, I think that's a good news
story, not a bad news story

00:08:46.900 --> 00:08:48.840
that we need to worry about.

00:08:48.840 --> 00:08:56.980
I, in the comments, saw that in
replace of the permanent exemption,

00:08:56.980 --> 00:08:59.300 position:56%
what the libraries seem to be asking

00:08:59.300 --> 00:09:02.190
for is all non-infringing
uses exemption.

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:05.350
And we've talked in other
panels about why there are a lot

00:09:05.350 --> 00:09:08.340
of dangers associated with
those types of proposals

00:09:08.340 --> 00:09:12.580
and why 1201(a) was designed not

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:18.230
to necessarily protect only
exclusive rights under section 106,

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:22.700
but also to provide a right of
access that is very important

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:25.050
and that needs to be preserved.

00:09:25.050 --> 00:09:30.470
When you get to the slightly
narrower approach of just--

00:09:30.470 --> 00:09:37.340
for 108 covered uses, I doubt
that that is going to go very far

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:41.560
in terms of reducing the number
of exemptions that libraries seek

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:46.710
because what I often read,
at least, is that libraries

00:09:46.710 --> 00:09:50.540 position:56%
and others are unhappy with the
scope of 108 as it currently exists.

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:54.500
And so, they would rather point to
Section 107 for most of the things

00:09:54.500 --> 00:09:58.760
that they want to do, in which
case you either get back to a kind

00:09:58.760 --> 00:10:04.370
of pseudo all non-infringement
uses-type of approach or you end

00:10:04.370 --> 00:10:07.740
up needing, even if you
cover all 108 activity,

00:10:07.740 --> 00:10:11.290
for people to come back every
three years and make new requests.

00:10:11.290 --> 00:10:15.000
So, I'm not sure that that would
have a very effective impact.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.170
I think what will have a
more effective impact is

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:21.660
that if the more streamlined
approach to renewals

00:10:21.660 --> 00:10:25.810
that was discussed yesterday is
adopted in some workable format,

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:29.410
the need to make permanent
these types

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:32.530
of exemptions becomes
a lot less important

00:10:32.530 --> 00:10:36.010
and you actually preserve the
ability to have some confidence

00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:39.040
of renewal, but you also
preserve the flexibility

00:10:39.040 --> 00:10:42.860 position:56%
of having the rulemaking there so
that if someone needs something new,

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:46.130
they don't have to go all
the way back to Congress.

00:10:46.130 --> 00:10:47.960
Again, they can come to you.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:49.260
Thanks.

00:10:49.260 --> 00:10:50.560
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:10:50.560 --> 00:10:53.050
Ms. Besek?

00:10:53.050 --> 00:10:56.650
&gt;&gt; June Besek: Well, specifically
with respect to an exception

00:10:56.650 --> 00:11:04.840 position:56%
for 108 activities, I can't help but
wonder why the libraries need it now

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:10.120 position:56%
when they haven't made such a
request, not necessarily with regard

00:11:10.120 --> 00:11:14.480 position:56%
to all 108-- specific 108 activities
over the last several years.

00:11:14.480 --> 00:11:17.640
It seems to me that if the
structure were that deficient,

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:19.200
they would have consistently asked

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:20.760
for that exemption,
and it's not there.

00:11:20.760 --> 00:11:23.280
So I'm not sure there's
really a basis.

00:11:23.280 --> 00:11:26.890
The second point I want to make
is I think Section 108 is broader

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:29.130
than people might realize.

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:32.480
I was on the Section 108
group, as were others here.

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:36.920
And, you know, it gives libraries
a fair amount of flexibility

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:40.690
with respect to providing
copies for users, for example.

00:11:40.690 --> 00:11:44.030
And so, I don't think
that we should assume

00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:46.030
that that would be
a narrow exception.

00:11:46.030 --> 00:11:49.940
And I think without-- I
think it is really akin

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:54.300 position:56%
to the no non-infringing uses, you
know, rather that you should be able

00:11:54.300 --> 00:12:00.080
to circumvent for any
non-infringing use or any fair use.

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:02.860
I think it falls in that
category and I would be reluctant

00:12:02.860 --> 00:12:04.590
to see that without more.

00:12:04.590 --> 00:12:05.890
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:12:05.890 --> 00:12:08.320
Ms. Cox, would you like
to respond to that?

00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:11.450 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: So of course, the
libraries-- Mr. Williams is correct,

00:12:11.450 --> 00:12:13.500
we do support the Unlocking
Technology Act,

00:12:13.500 --> 00:12:17.490
which would tie infringement
to circumvention.

00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:22.120
But as a next best option, you
know, we do very much believe

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:24.660
that permanent exemptions are
warranted in certain cases.

00:12:24.660 --> 00:12:27.460
For example, for assistive
technologies for the blind,

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:29.960
library services, authorized
entities that, you know,

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:34.010
were often providing
accessible formats for the blind,

00:12:34.010 --> 00:12:40.020
also for the audiovisual exceptions
for educators and students

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:43.040
at our colleges and universities,
for K through 12 educators.

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:45.800
These are all exemptions that
we have supported in the past.

00:12:45.800 --> 00:12:51.520
And in the most recent rulemaking
cycle, the NTIA recommendation

00:12:51.520 --> 00:12:56.930
to the Register in that report said
that they acknowledge the concerns

00:12:56.930 --> 00:13:02.090
by the rights holders who oppose
these exemptions, but that,

00:13:02.090 --> 00:13:03.390
you know, that emphasizing

00:13:03.390 --> 00:13:06.800
that these exemptions don't
legalize copyright infringement

00:13:06.800 --> 00:13:09.530
and that the record doesn't
show that the previous grants

00:13:09.530 --> 00:13:11.200
of similar exceptions
have led to piracy.

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:14.030
So I think in those cases,
it makes a lot of sense

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:16.400
to move towards a permanent
exemption,

00:13:16.400 --> 00:13:21.910
to expand our current 1201(d)
exemption to include the activities

00:13:21.910 --> 00:13:25.680
that are really important
to us, like these exemptions

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:26.980
that we request every time.

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:33.040
I think the Library Copyright
Alliance joined four different

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:37.650
proposals for exemptions
for audiovisual classes

00:13:37.650 --> 00:13:40.330
in this past rulemaking cycle.

00:13:40.330 --> 00:13:44.270
And, you know, it seems like
that that just keeps expanding.

00:13:44.270 --> 00:13:47.870
And so, I think having a permanent
exemption that is broad enough

00:13:47.870 --> 00:13:51.650
to cover these areas would make a
lot more sense than us having to go

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:54.990
through this every time, especially
when there isn't any evidence

00:13:54.990 --> 00:13:58.280
that infringement occurs
in having these exemptions.

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:01.520
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Can you
speak to Mr. Williams' point

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:05.720
that perhaps streamlining the
renewal would serve a great deal

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:08.150
of your concerns, while still
sort of leaving the door open

00:14:08.150 --> 00:14:10.630
in case there were changed
circumstances in the market

00:14:10.630 --> 00:14:13.570
or something or some reason,
you know, to sort of not etch it

00:14:13.570 --> 00:14:16.200
in statutory stone
and make it permanent?

00:14:16.200 --> 00:14:18.070
Could you live with that instead?

00:14:18.070 --> 00:14:19.370
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: Well,
I certainly think

00:14:19.370 --> 00:14:21.670
that streamlining the
process would of course help.

00:14:21.670 --> 00:14:23.590
But I would have to
see what the contours

00:14:23.590 --> 00:14:27.740
of that streamlined process would
look like because, you know,

00:14:27.740 --> 00:14:29.740
previous rulemaking
cycles, of course,

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.580
were I think much less
involved than they are today,

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:37.060
where you have a 400-page report
from the Copyright Office.

00:14:37.060 --> 00:14:40.830
I think that if there is
a, you know, presumption of

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:43.440
or an automatic renewal
unless there is evidence

00:14:43.440 --> 00:14:46.550
of changed circumstances, that
would certainly be helpful.

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:48.720
But what would be even
better, of course,

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:51.160
is that if there's a permanent
exemption where, you know,

00:14:51.160 --> 00:14:55.780
time and time again, the Copyright
Office is granting exemptions

00:14:55.780 --> 00:14:59.410
for persons who are blind
or disabled, for educators

00:14:59.410 --> 00:15:00.770
and educational institutions,

00:15:00.770 --> 00:15:03.330
for students in college
and universities.

00:15:03.330 --> 00:15:05.430
I think where there's
strong evidence

00:15:05.430 --> 00:15:09.750 position:56%
that there has not been infringement
as a results of these exemptions,

00:15:09.750 --> 00:15:13.550
it just makes sense to
make them permanent.

00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:14.850
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:15:14.850 --> 00:15:18.270
Could I just follow up
on the 108 question?

00:15:18.270 --> 00:15:22.830
We received some comments
that talked about the need

00:15:22.830 --> 00:15:26.770
to circumvent for-- of libraries
to circumvent for, for example,

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:31.940
preservation purposes and
they used the example of works

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:37.240
in obsolete format, which may
include TPMs in obsolete format.

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:40.240
I'm just wondering if you could
sort of elaborate on that.

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:44.800
And I wasn't totally clear
whether that sort of issue goes

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:48.330
to access controls or whether
the issue is copy controls.

00:15:48.330 --> 00:15:51.510
In other words, if
you have, you know,

00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:57.150
if a library receives a collection
of VHS tapes or something,

00:15:57.150 --> 00:15:59.160
is the issue with respect
to preservation

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:02.350
that the library can't access
the works or is it more

00:16:02.350 --> 00:16:05.520
that there is a copy control

00:16:05.520 --> 00:16:09.290
which would prevent
you from digitizing it?

00:16:09.290 --> 00:16:10.590
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: Well,
I think with the VHS,

00:16:10.590 --> 00:16:12.790
it would be a copy
control mechanism,

00:16:12.790 --> 00:16:15.410
not an access control mechanism.

00:16:15.410 --> 00:16:19.350
I think my colleague, Brandon
Butler, who actually works

00:16:19.350 --> 00:16:24.600
in a library may have more
information on this issue.

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:25.900
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: OK.

00:16:25.900 --> 00:16:27.200
OK. No, that's fine.

00:16:27.200 --> 00:16:28.800
Well, Mr. Dow?

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:30.100
&gt;&gt; Troy Dow: Thank you.

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:31.400
So, just a couple of points.

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:34.620
I served with June on
the Section 108 Committee

00:16:34.620 --> 00:16:38.560
and I had a similar reaction to the
proposal that there'd be some sort

00:16:38.560 --> 00:16:41.670
of exception that would apply to
Section 108 covered activities

00:16:41.670 --> 00:16:44.610
and that they apply to such
a broad range of activities,

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:47.450 position:56%
including things like
interlibrary loan, copies for users.

00:16:47.450 --> 00:16:49.930
I know that in the course
of our discussions there

00:16:49.930 --> 00:16:53.130
in the Section 108 group, we
talked extensively about the fact

00:16:53.130 --> 00:16:57.820
that copies for users for
private study was contemplated

00:16:57.820 --> 00:17:00.240
by many libraries to include
loaning of materials and providing

00:17:00.240 --> 00:17:04.030
of materials for personal review,
including the loaning of movies

00:17:04.030 --> 00:17:05.930
and things like that
for personal review.

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:07.720
And so, the notion that
you would have an exemption

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:10.480
that would allow you to
circumvent copy protection,

00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:15.310
to provide unencrypted copies
of expressive works as part

00:17:15.310 --> 00:17:17.410
of interlibrary loan
or as part of copies

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:20.140
for users I think would
be of concern to us.

00:17:20.140 --> 00:17:25.130
On the issue of not having
evidence of infringement,

00:17:25.130 --> 00:17:28.680
one of the concerns throughout
even with rulemaking processes,

00:17:28.680 --> 00:17:31.440
it's very, very difficult to tie
resulting acts of infringement

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:34.420
to the particular uses that
are being made pursuant

00:17:34.420 --> 00:17:35.720
to the exemptions, right?

00:17:35.720 --> 00:17:38.160
And so, if you have an exemption
to allow people to make copies

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:42.290
for a variety of uses,
tying then downstream--

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:45.390
if the result is that that
allows for circumvention

00:17:45.390 --> 00:17:49.420
to release unencrypted copies
of works then it's very hard

00:17:49.420 --> 00:17:51.930
to tie the downstream
copies of unencrypted copies

00:17:51.930 --> 00:17:53.720
to the first initial
copy that was made.

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:57.620
So, while there's not an abundance
of information in the record

00:17:57.620 --> 00:18:01.710 position:56%
to show infringements, it's actually
really hard to say what the impact

00:18:01.710 --> 00:18:03.430
of that is in the marketplace.

00:18:03.430 --> 00:18:07.160
The last thing I'll say is
that in terms of Section 108,

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:08.540
the other thing that
I think we learned

00:18:08.540 --> 00:18:10.250
in that process was it's very--

00:18:10.250 --> 00:18:12.840
that's a section that is
sort of technologically

00:18:12.840 --> 00:18:14.840
and marketplace-dependent.

00:18:14.840 --> 00:18:17.200
And part of the reason we
were gathered together to talk

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:20.410 position:56%
about Section 108 was because
technology had eclipsed the statute.

00:18:20.410 --> 00:18:22.200
And Congress had attempted
to make some updates

00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:23.500
in the context of the DMCA.

00:18:23.500 --> 00:18:26.510
And even those updates have been
eclipsed by time and by technology.

00:18:26.510 --> 00:18:28.440
And so, I think in
that sort of context,

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:30.810
in the types of things you're
talking about in 108 for things

00:18:30.810 --> 00:18:34.940 position:56%
like preservation, there's a benefit
to having a rulemaking process

00:18:34.940 --> 00:18:37.110
that can respond to those
changes in the marketplace,

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:38.920
to the specific technologies
that are being used,

00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:42.230 position:56%
to the specific concerns about what
the impact of allowing circumvention

00:18:42.230 --> 00:18:43.530
in those circumstances would be,

00:18:43.530 --> 00:18:45.710
that would not only
streamlined access

00:18:45.710 --> 00:18:48.140
to those exemptions along the
lines that were discussed but also

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:50.450
to have exemptions that are
tailored to the particular needs

00:18:50.450 --> 00:18:52.800
and to the particular concerns and
much better than you would be able

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:54.380
to do with a permanent exception

00:18:54.380 --> 00:18:55.950
that you might find
yourself looking at,

00:18:55.950 --> 00:18:59.920
very much like 108,becomes
quickly outdated.

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:01.220
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:19:01.220 --> 00:19:03.520
Mr. Love?

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:09.570
&gt;&gt; James Love: Thank you very much.

00:19:09.570 --> 00:19:14.900
If the permanent exceptions are by
statute only and the statute sort

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:17.280
of sets out all the conditions,
I think that the problem

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:20.840
in the past is you end up
with a fairly narrow statute

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:23.340
that is frustrating for
people who are supposed

00:19:23.340 --> 00:19:26.690
to be the intended
beneficiary of the statute.

00:19:26.690 --> 00:19:28.570
A better approach, in our mind,

00:19:28.570 --> 00:19:30.900
is if the statutory
mandates an exception

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:36.710
but permits the Copyright Office
to provide more information

00:19:36.710 --> 00:19:39.980 position:56%
about the contours of the exemption
at a later date, like so for example

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:44.450
if the statute-- let's
take the issue of that uses

00:19:44.450 --> 00:19:45.750
for people who are blind.

00:19:45.750 --> 00:19:52.890
You know, if it was to address the
obligations in the Marrakesh Treaty

00:19:52.890 --> 00:19:56.150
for people with disabilities.

00:19:56.150 --> 00:19:59.890
If the mandate was broad but there
was some sort of understanding

00:19:59.890 --> 00:20:03.200
that there could be, at some point,

00:20:03.200 --> 00:20:07.040
more contextual information
provided, if necessary,

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:12.870 position:56%
by the Copyright Office down the
road, it might be a better situation

00:20:12.870 --> 00:20:15.410
than trying to spell out
every particular issue

00:20:15.410 --> 00:20:17.330
that you might want
to do by statute.

00:20:17.330 --> 00:20:20.700
Another thing I think
that's important--

00:20:20.700 --> 00:20:24.820
I mean, we think that the idea of
more or less permanent exceptions--

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:27.310
I think permanent is a funny
word because nothing's really,

00:20:27.310 --> 00:20:29.080
even in a statute, permanent.

00:20:29.080 --> 00:20:31.760
So, I think what you're
talking about is durable

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.090
and persistent exceptions.

00:20:33.090 --> 00:20:39.990 position:56%
And so, I think the Copyright
Office surely should be able to do--

00:20:39.990 --> 00:20:42.310
you know, the three-year
thing I think is a mistake.

00:20:42.310 --> 00:20:45.090
I think a lot of people have
talked about that in other panels.

00:20:45.090 --> 00:20:49.300
One thing-- One of the reasons that
there's a high cost of developing

00:20:49.300 --> 00:20:52.630
and implementing both the
tools to use the exception and,

00:20:52.630 --> 00:20:56.850
as important I think, the
standards and the best practices

00:20:56.850 --> 00:20:58.730
for implementing exceptions.

00:20:58.730 --> 00:21:00.770
Now, if you want to have a
conversation, for example,

00:21:00.770 --> 00:21:03.950 position:56%
among authorized entities for people
that are blind or you want to talk

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:07.160 position:56%
about archivists or you want to talk
about maybe about auto-mechanics

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:11.330
or whatever group you want to
have, for them to sort of sort

00:21:11.330 --> 00:21:14.560
out the problems of the
different stakeholders

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:17.720
so that they're not just
looking at their own interests,

00:21:17.720 --> 00:21:19.960 position:56%
but they're looking at the interests
of third parties that are affected

00:21:19.960 --> 00:21:22.200
by the policies that
are implemented.

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:24.150
That can be a pretty
complicated thing.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:25.630
And then you want to, you
know, and then you have

00:21:25.630 --> 00:21:27.680
like a small enough number of
people, like the number of people

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:30.210
in this room, can kind of figure
out what that rule should be.

00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:33.960
And then, you want to like educate
like thousands of people, you know,

00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:35.990
as to how to sort of
use that standard and so

00:21:35.990 --> 00:21:37.620
that they do it in
an appropriate way.

00:21:37.620 --> 00:21:41.130
And then, you sort of say, but
this whole exercise is going

00:21:41.130 --> 00:21:43.510
to be revisited three
years from now.

00:21:43.510 --> 00:21:46.500
I mean, this kind of defeats the
idea that you're really serious

00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:49.570
about doing it in a thoughtful
way, where you have buy-in

00:21:49.570 --> 00:21:51.720
and implementation
that's really consistent.

00:21:51.720 --> 00:21:55.280
So I think that one of the
reasons for the more persistent

00:21:55.280 --> 00:21:59.790
and durable exceptions is the fact
that it really is time-consuming

00:21:59.790 --> 00:22:03.110
and costly to design
the tools for exceptions

00:22:03.110 --> 00:22:05.790 position:56%
and to implement them appropriately.

00:22:05.790 --> 00:22:07.510
Thank you.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:08.810
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:22:08.810 --> 00:22:11.650
Mr. Williams, did you have--

00:22:11.650 --> 00:22:14.470
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Just a quick
point to go back to something

