00:28:50.220 --> 00:28:52.290
And many of them would-- could lead

00:28:52.290 --> 00:28:57.100
to pretty bad things
for a lot of my members.

00:28:57.100 --> 00:29:04.840
So, I'm not-- color me skeptical
about that particular proposal.

00:29:04.840 --> 00:29:08.050
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. Geiger?

00:29:08.050 --> 00:29:09.730
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: Thanks.

00:29:09.730 --> 00:29:15.200
So unsurprisingly, we disagree that
the statute is currently working

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:16.810
with regard to security research.

00:29:16.810 --> 00:29:19.170
The temporary exemption
is a big deal for us.

00:29:19.170 --> 00:29:20.470
It is extremely helpful.

00:29:20.470 --> 00:29:23.910
But that aside, in talking
about the permanent exemption,

00:29:23.910 --> 00:29:28.780
as it stands right now, 1201does
chill very important security

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:33.070
research, research that will
help prevent harm to individuals

00:29:33.070 --> 00:29:35.060
and it will help prevent
breach of sensitive data.

00:29:35.060 --> 00:29:37.060
And we gave you an
example in our comments.

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:39.190
We have a researcher
that is employed

00:29:39.190 --> 00:29:41.690
by Rapid7 who is a diabetic.

00:29:41.690 --> 00:29:44.610
He wants to research his own
insulin pump, but was prevented

00:29:44.610 --> 00:29:46.610
from doing so, prior to
the temporary exemption,

00:29:46.610 --> 00:29:49.340
because of 1201 of the DMCA.

00:29:49.340 --> 00:29:51.520
In addition, a lot of
independent security researchers,

00:29:51.520 --> 00:29:54.230
folks that are not necessarily
employed by us but that we work

00:29:54.230 --> 00:30:00.200 position:56%
with to help improve our own
security products, they are chilled.

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:03.370
That is, they don't engage in the
research to begin with or many

00:30:03.370 --> 00:30:05.060
of them actually receive
cease-and-desist letters

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:06.790
that reference the DMCA.

00:30:06.790 --> 00:30:10.470
This is again prior to
the temporary exemption.

00:30:10.470 --> 00:30:14.140
So we don't think that it works
and we think that this issue

00:30:14.140 --> 00:30:17.160
of security research in software
is becoming a lot more important.

00:30:17.160 --> 00:30:20.360
As discussed previously, we are
seeing this explosion of software,

00:30:20.360 --> 00:30:22.610
both in the physical
world and virtually.

00:30:22.610 --> 00:30:24.060
And there are a lot
more security flaws

00:30:24.060 --> 00:30:25.360
than there are people to fix it.

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:29.180
And in many cases,
manufacturers either don't know

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:31.620
about the software
flaws or they turn--

00:30:31.620 --> 00:30:33.620
they're willfully ignorant of them.

00:30:33.620 --> 00:30:35.990
Part of the problem with
voluntary agreements,

00:30:35.990 --> 00:30:38.480
and this goes to the
requirement of authorization

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:42.600
in the permanent exception, is
that it hampers independence.

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:44.380
It means that the manufacturers
themselves get

00:30:44.380 --> 00:30:47.350
to control completely how the
security research takes place

00:30:47.350 --> 00:30:48.650
and what the publication is like.

00:30:48.650 --> 00:30:50.120
And if you're a manufacturer

00:30:50.120 --> 00:30:52.130
that doesn't support
independent security research

00:30:52.130 --> 00:30:54.800
or if you are a manufacturer
that has something to hide,

00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:58.640
as Volkswagen, for example,

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:01.380
might then that will make the
research a lot less effective

00:31:01.380 --> 00:31:02.960
and not as independent.

00:31:02.960 --> 00:31:04.980
There are also several
other problems

00:31:04.980 --> 00:31:07.970
with the permanent exception,
one of which is this requirement

00:31:07.970 --> 00:31:09.930
that it violate no other law.

00:31:09.930 --> 00:31:12.980
The CFAA is very, very broad.

00:31:12.980 --> 00:31:14.280
It's very ambiguous.

00:31:14.280 --> 00:31:17.380
It is the subject right now of
some pretty sharp circuit splits.

00:31:17.380 --> 00:31:20.780
So you're importing a lot of the
ambiguity from these other laws

00:31:20.780 --> 00:31:25.520
into 1201, laws that have
their own chilling problems

00:31:25.520 --> 00:31:29.180
and doing it largely for
non-copyright reasons.

00:31:29.180 --> 00:31:31.320
There's also a part of the
permanent exemption that says

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:34.730
that the information derived from
the research cannot be maintained

00:31:34.730 --> 00:31:37.000
in such a way that could
facilitate infringement

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:38.760
or violation of another law.

00:31:38.760 --> 00:31:40.510
Well, what happens if
you're a security researcher

00:31:40.510 --> 00:31:42.030
and you've contacted
the manufacturer

00:31:42.030 --> 00:31:43.710
about a problem in their product?

00:31:43.710 --> 00:31:46.870
They do nothing and the standard
practice is that eventually,

00:31:46.870 --> 00:31:49.040
you will make that
disclosure public.

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:51.010
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Well, doesn't the
statute sort of contemplate by that

00:31:51.010 --> 00:31:53.040
by saying it's a factor
that should be considered?

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:57.560 position:56%
And maybe in that specific use case,
it would make sense to not stick it

00:31:57.560 --> 00:31:59.590
with the manufacturer,
but to go broader?

00:31:59.590 --> 00:32:00.890
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: Absolutely.

00:32:00.890 --> 00:32:02.430
The fact that it's just
a factor as opposed

00:32:02.430 --> 00:32:03.920
to an outright requirement, sure.

00:32:03.920 --> 00:32:07.600 position:56%
But both factors are cutting against
the security researcher, right?

00:32:07.600 --> 00:32:10.560
One is, you know, if
they've publicly disclosed it

00:32:10.560 --> 00:32:13.520
and then others can use
that for nefarious purposes,

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:14.930
which is part of the point, right?

00:32:14.930 --> 00:32:16.630
Part of the reason why
you publicly disclose is

00:32:16.630 --> 00:32:18.850
to encourage a manufacturer
to actually correct their flaw

00:32:18.850 --> 00:32:20.670
if they haven't been previously.

00:32:20.670 --> 00:32:24.960
And then, the second was
whether the information is solely

00:32:24.960 --> 00:32:27.930
for the purpose of
benefiting the manufacturer,

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:29.550
the owner of the computer system.

00:32:29.550 --> 00:32:31.560
And a lot of times, security
researchers are doing this

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:32.920
for the benefit of the public,

00:32:32.920 --> 00:32:35.090
not necessarily the owner
of the computer system.

00:32:35.090 --> 00:32:37.770
I want to make three
other points really quick

00:32:37.770 --> 00:32:39.070
because we've talked about--

00:32:39.070 --> 00:32:40.370 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Right, keep it quick

00:32:40.370 --> 00:32:41.670
because we'll have
follow-up questions.

00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:42.970
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: I'll
talk about it quickly.

00:32:42.970 --> 00:32:44.270
We talked about this in
previous panels, right?

00:32:44.270 --> 00:32:48.910
So this idea of an
embedded software exception

00:32:48.910 --> 00:32:52.410 position:56%
or in the temporary exception, we're
talking about consumer devices.

00:32:52.410 --> 00:32:54.050
These lines are blurring, right?

00:32:54.050 --> 00:32:56.500
And things that are embedded
in software now may not be--

00:32:56.500 --> 00:32:59.650
or embedded in devices now may
not be in devices in the future,

00:32:59.650 --> 00:33:01.800
consumer devices, likewise.

00:33:01.800 --> 00:33:03.900
Security researchers work
on more than just devices.

00:33:03.900 --> 00:33:05.200
They work on networks.

00:33:05.200 --> 00:33:07.200
They work on completely
virtual software.

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:09.660
Then what counts as a
consumer device is also

00:33:09.660 --> 00:33:13.990
in many cases a business device
or is used by infrastructure.

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:16.780
And we want to encourage that
kind of security research.

00:33:16.780 --> 00:33:19.090
So, thank you.

00:33:19.090 --> 00:33:22.470
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: I'd like
to ask you a follow-up

00:33:22.470 --> 00:33:24.620
