00:41:45.090 --> 00:41:50.580
of treat the legal protections of
TPMs as a privilege, not a right.

00:41:50.580 --> 00:41:54.720 position:56%
And that you associate the privilege
with obligations on the person

00:41:54.720 --> 00:41:57.260
who wants the state to
enforce the right for them,

00:41:57.260 --> 00:42:00.240
recognizing that there
are these competing areas.

00:42:00.240 --> 00:42:07.790
I think that that would-- Some of
the problems you have right now

00:42:07.790 --> 00:42:13.520
of people are looking for permanent
exceptions and things like that.

00:42:13.520 --> 00:42:19.160
I mean, sometimes it's because
the practices in the TPM, I think,

00:42:19.160 --> 00:42:21.860
are so inconsistent
with public policy.

00:42:21.860 --> 00:42:30.350
And it's just the-- it's
obvious that, you know,

00:42:30.350 --> 00:42:32.940
you want to have some
carve-outs, some sort of it.

00:42:32.940 --> 00:42:35.250
But people always raise
these issues like, well,

00:42:35.250 --> 00:42:37.980
do you anticipate all the
problems and things like that.

00:42:37.980 --> 00:42:40.670
I think just starting with the
idea that everything is protected

00:42:40.670 --> 00:42:43.580
and you have to kind of
claw back the exceptions,

00:42:43.580 --> 00:42:45.050
I think that creates
a lot of the problems.

00:42:45.050 --> 00:42:47.860
If you sort of create the
environment where you have to sort

00:42:47.860 --> 00:42:51.510 position:56%
of make a case for the exceptions or
at least describe what you believe

00:42:51.510 --> 00:42:53.940
that you've made the
case at a very minimum.

00:42:53.940 --> 00:42:56.980
I think it begins to make the
whole process more manageable.

00:42:56.980 --> 00:42:59.860
Also, I'm a little concerned
about the relationship

00:42:59.860 --> 00:43:02.890
between trade agreements and what
you're doing in this proceeding

00:43:02.890 --> 00:43:06.170
because you're-- the government is
involved in these trade agreements

00:43:06.170 --> 00:43:10.000
where you're creating exceptions
about what we have to do

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:11.980
within the context of
the trade agreements.

00:43:11.980 --> 00:43:14.400
And then they're creating
these investor state agreements

00:43:14.400 --> 00:43:17.300
where people can bring
lawsuits against the--

00:43:17.300 --> 00:43:21.270
or bring arbitrations against the
United States around those things

00:43:21.270 --> 00:43:23.650
if their expectations aren't
met and things like that.

00:43:23.650 --> 00:43:26.070
And I think that it would be
important for the Copyright Office,

00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:29.030 position:56%
to the extent that they're modifying
the rules or changing the rules

00:43:29.030 --> 00:43:32.300
in this thing to also talk to the
United States Trade Representative

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:35.650
to make sure that they're
ensuring there's enough flexibility

00:43:35.650 --> 00:43:36.950
in our agreements.

00:43:36.950 --> 00:43:39.270 position:56%
So if we change our philosophy about
how to do these technical locks

00:43:39.270 --> 00:43:41.880
on things across a wide
range of industries,

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:45.710
not just the motion picture
industry or the book industry,

00:43:45.710 --> 00:43:47.880
but in these areas that
involve automobiles

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:51.520
and consumer electronic devices
and all the other things affected

00:43:51.520 --> 00:43:55.090
by the trade agreements,
that we're not in a situation

00:43:55.090 --> 00:43:57.230
where you're trying to do one thing

00:43:57.230 --> 00:43:59.080
where the United States
Trade Office--

00:43:59.080 --> 00:44:03.010
Trade Representative is
making that difficult.

00:44:03.010 --> 00:44:04.310
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

