unaffiliated with an organization

00:46:05.600 --> 00:46:07.580
and entities such as Rapid7.

00:46:07.580 --> 00:46:10.050
&gt;&gt; Harley Geiger: So, for
folks that are unaffiliated

00:46:10.050 --> 00:46:11.500
with an organization, they--

00:46:11.500 --> 00:46:13.770
that's typically where the
cease-and-desist letters tend

00:46:13.770 --> 00:46:15.070
to have the most impact.

00:46:15.070 --> 00:46:16.430
If you're affiliated
with an organization,

00:46:16.430 --> 00:46:20.440 position:56%
then you have more resources to draw
on to evaluate your legal claims.

00:46:20.440 --> 00:46:22.540
We play in both worlds.

00:46:22.540 --> 00:46:25.290
We work a lot with independent
security researchers and try

00:46:25.290 --> 00:46:27.200
to help be a steward
to that community.

00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:30.380
But we also have our
own researchers.

00:46:30.380 --> 00:46:34.280
And in cases where you have
an institutional affiliation,

00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:36.310
a lot of times you just
see it ignored, right?

00:46:36.310 --> 00:46:38.340
You just see-- you see the
cease-and-desist letter just kind

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:40.670 position:56%
of ignored and sort of, well, if you
want to go to litigation over this

00:46:40.670 --> 00:46:42.210
for real, then we'll do that.

00:46:42.210 --> 00:46:44.350
And often, it doesn't
get to that stage.

00:46:44.350 --> 00:46:46.910
Either way, the system is broken.

00:46:46.910 --> 00:46:49.090
It may have made more
sense when it was enacted,

00:46:49.090 --> 00:46:50.640
but as it is now, it's not working.

00:46:50.640 --> 00:46:53.600
And we have-- I mean, cybersecurity
is a national priority.

00:46:53.600 --> 00:46:54.900
Everybody recognizes that.

00:46:54.900 --> 00:46:58.680
So why in the world would we wait
for bad cases to be litigated?

00:46:58.680 --> 00:46:59.980
Two other points.

00:46:59.980 --> 00:47:04.520
One is when it comes to not
violating any other law,

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:06.670
most of these other
laws, including the CFAA,

00:47:06.670 --> 00:47:09.130
provide a private right of action.

00:47:09.130 --> 00:47:11.850
It would seem odd to us to--

00:47:11.850 --> 00:47:14.920
If the security research
is violating the CFAA,

00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:19.550 position:56%
why suddenly the permanent exception
protection should also fall away?

00:47:19.550 --> 00:47:20.900
I mean, the punishments under CFAA

00:47:20.900 --> 00:47:23.770
and other laws are
already relatively harsh.

00:47:23.770 --> 00:47:25.840 position:56%
So why add onto that with copyright?

00:47:25.840 --> 00:47:27.770
I don't understand why
that would play into it?

00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:30.860
And in addition, if it's a matter
of violating a licensing agreement,

00:47:30.860 --> 00:47:35.140
then you do have recourse
through breach of contract to go

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:36.440
after the researcher there.

00:47:36.440 --> 00:47:37.950
So, there are other
avenues that don't need

00:47:37.950 --> 00:47:41.180 position:56%
to necessarily rope in Section 1201.

00:47:41.180 --> 00:47:43.000
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Can I ask
