00:54:48.600 --> 00:54:50.380
So Mr. Dow?

00:54:50.380 --> 00:54:52.190
&gt;&gt; Troy Dow: Just two
thoughts very quickly.

00:54:52.190 --> 00:54:56.230
One is-- I think this goes to Mr.
Williams' point that this notion

00:54:56.230 --> 00:54:59.210
of interoperability-- I don't
know what Mr. Geiger's company

00:54:59.210 --> 00:55:00.510
does either.

00:55:00.510 --> 00:55:02.270
But just listening to
him, I have every belief

00:55:02.270 --> 00:55:03.710
that what he does is in good faith.

00:55:03.710 --> 00:55:07.110
But what we've seen even in
some of the CSS litigation is

00:55:07.110 --> 00:55:09.870
that we've had people who've tried
to take advantage of the exceptions

00:55:09.870 --> 00:55:12.390
for things like security
testing and interoperability,

00:55:12.390 --> 00:55:16.790
but things that really were just
about removing content protection

00:55:16.790 --> 00:55:20.050 position:56%
from movies and other entertainment.

00:55:20.050 --> 00:55:21.580
And so, unfortunately--

00:55:21.580 --> 00:55:23.300
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: And so, in those
instances, they're doing it

00:55:23.300 --> 00:55:26.220
in the name of research or how
do they link that together?

00:55:26.220 --> 00:55:28.530
&gt;&gt; Troy Dow: Well, so for
example, in the Corley case,

00:55:28.530 --> 00:55:30.680
you had a defense that
was put forward that said

00:55:30.680 --> 00:55:33.130
that what was going on there was
really just a matter of trying

00:55:33.130 --> 00:55:36.880
to make DVDs interoperable
with Linux computer systems

00:55:36.880 --> 00:55:39.040
because they said there
wasn't a Linux player

00:55:39.040 --> 00:55:40.340
that could play those DVDs.

00:55:40.340 --> 00:55:42.420
In fact, there were licensed
Linux players at the time.

00:55:42.420 --> 00:55:44.760
But the problem was that
the way they preferred

00:55:44.760 --> 00:55:47.040
to make those movies
viewable on a Linux player was

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:48.340
to remove the copy protection.

00:55:48.340 --> 00:55:50.360
Remove the encryption so they
would play on any player, right?

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:52.690
That makes the movie
interoperable by making sure

00:55:52.690 --> 00:55:54.730
that there are no protections,
right?

00:55:54.730 --> 00:55:58.750
Now, the court saw through that and
didn't see the permanent exemption

00:55:58.750 --> 00:56:00.260
as applicable in that circumstance.

00:56:00.260 --> 00:56:03.410
But it was an example of
somebody who was not a good actor

00:56:03.410 --> 00:56:05.990
who was trying to leverage some of
these exemptions for purposes other

00:56:05.990 --> 00:56:07.290
than the ones that were intended.

00:56:07.290 --> 00:56:10.270
And we need to be mindful of
the ability of people to do

00:56:10.270 --> 00:56:11.570
that in the way they're crafted.

00:56:11.570 --> 00:56:14.680
The second point I was going
to make, and this is sort

00:56:14.680 --> 00:56:17.080
of probably taking my Disney
hat off and putting back

00:56:17.080 --> 00:56:20.550
on my former Judiciary Committee
counsel hat, that this interaction

00:56:20.550 --> 00:56:24.540
between Mr. Geiger and Mr. Mohr
I think just highlights the fact

00:56:24.540 --> 00:56:27.380
that these exceptions in
the statute were very,

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:30.160
very carefully negotiated,
down to every word

00:56:30.160 --> 00:56:32.970
between the relevant
impacted parties.

00:56:32.970 --> 00:56:35.970
If we just start going through
and crossing out words, we start--

00:56:35.970 --> 00:56:37.800
we start upending a
balance that was struck.

00:56:37.800 --> 00:56:39.300
Now, whether or not
this balance continues

00:56:39.300 --> 00:56:41.380
to work today is a
totally separate question.

00:56:41.380 --> 00:56:45.110
But the notion that somehow we
could just start rejiggering things

00:56:45.110 --> 00:56:47.100
and that we would maintain
the type of balance

00:56:47.100 --> 00:56:49.390
that was maintained
I think is a concern.

00:56:49.390 --> 00:56:52.240
If Mr. Mohr and Mr.
Geiger go off and figure

00:56:52.240 --> 00:56:54.500
out what the right
modifications are to it

00:56:54.500 --> 00:56:57.510
and it doesn't implicate the types
of concerns I was referring to,

00:56:57.510 --> 00:56:58.810
that may be another thing.

00:56:58.810 --> 00:57:02.020
But I think this sort of counsels
towards a consensus-based approach

00:57:02.020 --> 00:57:04.800
to these things.

00:57:04.800 --> 00:57:07.120
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Ms. Koberidze?

00:57:07.120 --> 00:57:11.730
&gt;&gt; Maryna Koberidze: I wanted
to pick up on something

00:57:11.730 --> 00:57:17.500
that Mr. Love mentioned
regarding European Directive.

00:57:17.500 --> 00:57:20.760
Europe went with another
approach than the US.

00:57:20.760 --> 00:57:22.810
The US decided to give
fewer exemptions

00:57:22.810 --> 00:57:26.110
and to go with rulemaking process.

00:57:26.110 --> 00:57:31.850
European Union went with
giving an originally long list

00:57:31.850 --> 00:57:33.160
with exemptions.

00:57:33.160 --> 00:57:38.130
But some of the countries decided
to provide a mediation process.

00:57:38.130 --> 00:57:44.720
And maybe with permanent exemptions
under 1201, that could be an option

00:57:44.720 --> 00:57:49.280
for the parties to get into that
mediation process, like we just saw

00:57:49.280 --> 00:57:50.660
with Mr. Geiger and Mr. Mohr.

00:57:50.660 --> 00:57:53.600
They are open to discussion.

00:57:53.600 --> 00:57:54.900
And that would be helpful.

00:57:54.900 --> 00:57:59.180
So for example, it could be
like the first step would be

00:57:59.180 --> 00:58:02.780
for the interested beneficiary
of the exemption to come forward

00:58:02.780 --> 00:58:05.590
and contact the copyright
holder and say,

00:58:05.590 --> 00:58:11.300
we would like to make certain uses
under the permanent exemption.

00:58:11.300 --> 00:58:14.200
Do you agree or not?

00:58:14.200 --> 00:58:18.140
If they do not, then the
intended beneficiaries could go

00:58:18.140 --> 00:58:21.510
and request certain agency.

00:58:21.510 --> 00:58:26.140
In this case, it would be
Copyright Office to help

00:58:26.140 --> 00:58:31.120
to accommodate the access
or third party assistance,

00:58:31.120 --> 00:58:33.690
whatever is applicable
in the specific--

00:58:33.690 --> 00:58:36.770
under a specific permanent
exemption.

00:58:36.770 --> 00:58:38.250
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:58:38.250 --> 00:58:40.620
I do think we need to move on.

00:58:40.620 --> 00:58:45.300
I want to turn to talking
about proposals

00:58:45.300 --> 00:58:47.440
for new permanent exemptions.

00:58:47.440 --> 00:58:51.190
And I wanted to start
with a proposal

00:58:51.190 --> 00:58:55.030
that we saw pretty
substantial agreement

00:58:55.030 --> 00:58:56.460
on in the written comments.

00:58:56.460 --> 00:58:58.500
And that would be an exemption

00:58:58.500 --> 00:59:01.090
for the print-disabled
and visually impaired.

00:59:01.090 --> 00:59:07.670
As you know, the current exemption
applies to literary works protected

00:59:07.670 --> 00:59:12.930
by TPMs that prevent read-aloud
functionality or screen readers

00:59:12.930 --> 00:59:15.340
or other assistive technologies.

00:59:15.340 --> 00:59:18.440
I would be interested
in your thoughts

00:59:18.440 --> 00:59:22.030
about whether Congress
might consider making

00:59:22.030 --> 00:59:24.030
that specific exemption permanent.

00:59:24.030 --> 00:59:28.260
If so, whether the current
language is sufficient

00:59:28.260 --> 00:59:31.360
or whether it should
be altered in some way.

00:59:31.360 --> 00:59:35.240
And I'd like to start
with Mr. Cazares.

00:59:35.240 --> 00:59:41.290
&gt;&gt; Gabe Cazares: I think that I
first and foremost would be remiss

00:59:41.290 --> 00:59:45.810
if I didn't recognize the effort
that both the publishing industry

00:59:45.810 --> 00:59:51.770
and the libraries have done in the
last few years to try and ensure

00:59:51.770 --> 00:59:55.390
that accessibility is
something that's incorporated

00:59:55.390 --> 00:59:56.690
from the beginning.

00:59:56.690 --> 01:00:01.900
I think Ms. Cox brought up a
good point on the exemptions

01:00:01.900 --> 01:00:06.740 position:56%
that the libraries really do rely on
to ensure that assistive technology

01:00:06.740 --> 01:00:10.300
and other technologies
used by the blind

01:00:10.300 --> 01:00:13.080 position:56%
and visually impaired are available.

01:00:13.080 --> 01:00:17.540
And likewise the publishers have
done great work with their members

01:00:17.540 --> 01:00:20.440
to ensure that products are
being produced accessibly.

01:00:20.440 --> 01:00:26.210
Having said that, I think that
it's safe to say that for people

01:00:26.210 --> 01:00:28.620 position:56%
who are blind and visually impaired,

01:00:28.620 --> 01:00:31.760
that circumstance certainly
isn't going to change.

01:00:31.760 --> 01:00:34.890
I expect to be blind
three years from now.

01:00:34.890 --> 01:00:40.490
So I think that the discussion
is worth having on setting

01:00:40.490 --> 01:00:42.440
up a permanent exemption.

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:48.630
I think that the language that
we have now is worth revisiting,

01:00:48.630 --> 01:00:51.480
with all of the interested
stakeholders.

01:00:51.480 --> 01:00:53.060
Accessibility has been something

01:00:53.060 --> 01:00:57.390
that has quite literally
taken a village to try

01:00:57.390 --> 01:00:58.870
and bring to the mainstream.

01:00:58.870 --> 01:01:02.210
So I think that the discussions
that we've spearheaded,

01:01:02.210 --> 01:01:05.850
both with the libraries and the
publishers and the discussion

01:01:05.850 --> 01:01:08.050
that we're having now
is a good start.

01:01:08.050 --> 01:01:11.060
But I definitely know that
the National Federation

01:01:11.060 --> 01:01:14.820
of the Blind is supportive
of such permanent exemption.

01:01:14.820 --> 01:01:16.120
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

01:01:16.120 --> 01:01:17.420
May I ask a follow-up?

01:01:17.420 --> 01:01:23.320 position:56%
I just would be curious to know your
views on sort of how the market--

01:01:23.320 --> 01:01:28.070 position:56%
and you mentioned this at the outset
of your statement-- is responding.

01:01:28.070 --> 01:01:32.360 position:56%
Have you noticed a change over time,

01:01:32.360 --> 01:01:39.780
an increase in accessible
format copies becoming available

01:01:39.780 --> 01:01:45.740
in the marketplace, such
that, you know, maybe the need

01:01:45.740 --> 01:01:48.940
to circumvent may be diminished?

01:01:48.940 --> 01:01:53.210
&gt;&gt; Gabe Cazares: So I certainly
don't think that we're at a point

01:01:53.210 --> 01:01:55.350
where the need to circumvent
needs to be diminished,

01:01:55.350 --> 01:01:59.320
particularly in the
realm of education.

01:01:59.320 --> 01:02:03.060
There's still a lot of work
that needs to be done to ensure

01:02:03.060 --> 01:02:08.140
that eBooks and digital books that
are produced particularly with,

01:02:08.140 --> 01:02:11.510
you know, the DRM, are accessible.

01:02:11.510 --> 01:02:15.550 position:56%
What we're finding now is that a
lot of time authorized entities have

01:02:15.550 --> 01:02:19.580
to then take such materials and
ensure that they're accessible.

01:02:19.580 --> 01:02:23.520
I think that we're doing-- we're
making significant progress.

01:02:23.520 --> 01:02:26.520
But I don't think we're
at the happy-go-lucky day

01:02:26.520 --> 01:02:28.980
where I can safely
say that everything

01:02:28.980 --> 01:02:32.580
that is produced digitally,
particularly in the literary realm,

01:02:32.580 --> 01:02:35.550
is accessible from the beginning.

01:02:35.550 --> 01:02:36.850
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Great.

01:02:36.850 --> 01:02:38.150
Thank you.

01:02:38.150 --> 01:02:40.920
Ms. Cox?

01:02:40.920 --> 01:02:44.020
&gt;&gt; Krista L. Cox: So, you've heard
me say earlier, but, of course,

01:02:44.020 --> 01:02:47.290
we agree with the position of the
National Federation of the Blind

01:02:47.290 --> 01:02:50.520
that these permanent
exemptions are necessary.

01:02:50.520 --> 01:02:51.970
And I would just add a few points,

01:02:51.970 --> 01:02:56.470
that as the Obama administration
earlier this year submitted the

01:02:56.470 --> 01:03:01.070
Marrakesh Treaty for
ratification by the Senate,

01:03:01.070 --> 01:03:04.520
also submitted implementing
legislation, it's really important

01:03:04.520 --> 01:03:07.680
to note that if the Marrakesh
Treaty comes into force,

01:03:07.680 --> 01:03:13.130
that in order to comply with the
treaty and really make it useful,

01:03:13.130 --> 01:03:16.270
it would be good to have
that permanent exemption

01:03:16.270 --> 01:03:18.900
to ensure compliance
with the treaty.

01:03:18.900 --> 01:03:24.690
Additionally, as Mr. Cazares
pointed out, that even though, yes,

01:03:24.690 --> 01:03:28.720
there are more works being
produced digitally, it doesn't mean

01:03:28.720 --> 01:03:32.150
that those works are
necessarily accessible,

01:03:32.150 --> 01:03:34.260 position:56%
especially in the educational realm.

01:03:34.260 --> 01:03:37.860
Our libraries work very often with
the disability services offices

01:03:37.860 --> 01:03:41.590
to ensure that we are able
to provide accessible formats

01:03:41.590 --> 01:03:45.450
of various textbooks,
which are often not created

01:03:45.450 --> 01:03:48.240
in an accessible format
from the start.

01:03:48.240 --> 01:03:49.730
You know, we would
love for everything

01:03:49.730 --> 01:03:55.440
to be immediately accessible for
our users that are print-disabled.

01:03:55.440 --> 01:03:58.770
But that's simply not
the case today.

01:03:58.770 --> 01:04:02.310
And just, you know,
I think the example

01:04:02.310 --> 01:04:07.110 position:56%
of the print-disabled also ties into
this question of interoperability

01:04:07.110 --> 01:04:10.160
because oftentimes individuals

01:04:10.160 --> 01:04:13.510
with print disabilities have a
specific device that they use.

01:04:13.510 --> 01:04:19.650
And while it might be accessible on
one format on, you know, an iPad,

01:04:19.650 --> 01:04:22.250
it might not be accessible
on a Kindle.

01:04:22.250 --> 01:04:26.300
And it's really unfair to ask
someone who is print-disabled

01:04:26.300 --> 01:04:30.260
to buy five different devices to
find the one that works for them.

01:04:30.260 --> 01:04:34.420
And this actually came up, I
believe, in the rulemaking process

01:04:34.420 --> 01:04:38.030
where the joint reply comments from
rights holders groups like the AAP,

01:04:38.030 --> 01:04:43.290
MPAA, RIAA criticized
the American Federation

01:04:43.290 --> 01:04:47.770
for the Blind's evidence showing
that four of the five works

01:04:47.770 --> 01:04:51.300
that they looked at were
not accessible to them.

01:04:51.300 --> 01:04:53.520
They actually found that three
of those four were accessible.

01:04:53.520 --> 01:04:55.750
They just weren't accessible
on the format that--

01:04:55.750 --> 01:04:59.270
and the platform that was being
used to test this in the evidence.

01:04:59.270 --> 01:05:02.550
So I think it's really
important to ensure that,

01:05:02.550 --> 01:05:04.480
especially for the print-disabled,

01:05:04.480 --> 01:05:12.370
that you're not restricting
that exemption.

01:05:12.370 --> 01:05:14.640
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

01:05:14.640 --> 01:05:17.540
Ms. Besek?

01:05:17.540 --> 01:05:19.340
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Microphone.

01:05:19.340 --> 01:05:23.500 position:56%
&gt;&gt; June M. Besek: This is an
appropriate area for Congress to act

01:05:23.500 --> 01:05:28.020
because I think the history
of the rulemaking indicates

01:05:28.020 --> 01:05:31.560
that this is an exemption that's
regularly been sought and granted

01:05:31.560 --> 01:05:32.860
without a lot of opposition.

01:05:32.860 --> 01:05:36.830
And I think there's strong public
policy reasons for raising it

01:05:36.830 --> 01:05:38.340
to the level of a permanent
exemption.

01:05:38.340 --> 01:05:40.260
So, I would favor it in general.

01:05:40.260 --> 01:05:43.430
Although, you know, I
can't say sitting here

01:05:43.430 --> 01:05:45.810
that the exact formulation,
you know,

01:05:45.810 --> 01:05:48.370
of a past rulemaking
is the correct one.

01:05:48.370 --> 01:05:49.930
And that's something that
we would have to look at.

01:05:49.930 --> 01:05:52.700
I do have some concerns
about the, you know,

01:05:52.700 --> 01:05:56.820
accessibility discussion
that we just had.

01:05:56.820 --> 01:06:01.240
And, you know, because there's
also the other side of the coin.

01:06:01.240 --> 01:06:03.370
You don't want to discourage
the market

01:06:03.370 --> 01:06:06.950
for creating accessible versions
for other types of devices as well.

01:06:06.950 --> 01:06:09.600
So, there are both sides
of that to consider.

01:06:09.600 --> 01:06:11.980
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Do you have a
view as to whether a discussion

01:06:11.980 --> 01:06:14.610
about implementing a permanent
exemption along this line should be

01:06:14.610 --> 01:06:18.720
limited towards sort of
the general subject matter

01:06:18.720 --> 01:06:21.010
of the prior exemptions for
the print-disabled as opposed

01:06:21.010 --> 01:06:24.010
to accessibility or assistive
technology more broadly?

01:06:24.010 --> 01:06:25.400
I mean, we've received
written comments

01:06:25.400 --> 01:06:28.380
of an organization
representing individuals

01:06:28.380 --> 01:06:31.580
with degenerative diseases,
not necessarily related--

01:06:31.580 --> 01:06:34.360
so, not necessarily related
to eBooks or, you know,

01:06:34.360 --> 01:06:36.710
accessing books, but
maybe, you know,

01:06:36.710 --> 01:06:39.530
playing a videogame, for example.

01:06:39.530 --> 01:06:42.030
&gt;&gt; June M. Besek: At this
point, I think because part

01:06:42.030 --> 01:06:44.820
of my rationale is
that there has been--

01:06:44.820 --> 01:06:47.830
there have been a series of
exemptions already granted,

01:06:47.830 --> 01:06:50.190
I would mean the print-disabled.

01:06:50.190 --> 01:06:55.270
That doesn't mean that other
groups couldn't seek in the future,

01:06:55.270 --> 01:06:57.530
you know, an exemption
under the rulemaking.

01:06:57.530 --> 01:07:01.560 position:56%
And perhaps at some point, you know,
that that would be deemed worthy

01:07:01.560 --> 01:07:03.760
of a permanent exemption.

01:07:03.760 --> 01:07:10.870
But I think it would be
premature to do that right now.

01:07:10.870 --> 01:07:12.170
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. Williams?

01:07:12.170 --> 01:07:13.470
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Thank you.

01:07:13.470 --> 01:07:18.050
I think we would agree that this is
an important exemption that's been

01:07:18.050 --> 01:07:21.490
in existence now for some time.

01:07:21.490 --> 01:07:24.220
I think you're also right to say
that there's generally consensus

01:07:24.220 --> 01:07:27.560
that it should continue
to exist and be renewed.

01:07:27.560 --> 01:07:28.860
And at this point in time,

01:07:28.860 --> 01:07:33.030
the market isn't adequately
addressing the problem

01:07:33.030 --> 01:07:37.510
and that's why we don't oppose
the existence of the exemption.

01:07:37.510 --> 01:07:40.340
I think the streamlined
renewal process, again,

01:07:40.340 --> 01:07:44.490
is something that would be more
effective at addressing this

01:07:44.490 --> 01:07:48.890
than trying to make the exemption
permanent for a couple of reasons.

01:07:48.890 --> 01:07:53.130
The first is my understanding
is that there are formats

01:07:53.130 --> 01:07:55.430
in development that
are going to roll

01:07:55.430 --> 01:07:59.070
out that will make this
problem much less significant

01:07:59.070 --> 01:08:01.740
if it doesn't go away.

01:08:01.740 --> 01:08:05.300
There's EPUB-3 and HTML-5 which
I understand are both going

01:08:05.300 --> 01:08:08.210
to help address these issues.

01:08:08.210 --> 01:08:10.910
And so, if that were the case

01:08:10.910 --> 01:08:14.920 position:56%
and circumvention became unnecessary
then there wouldn't be a need

01:08:14.920 --> 01:08:20.830
to have an exemption sitting in the
statute when we could just renew it

01:08:20.830 --> 01:08:22.840
through the rulemaking process.

01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:26.940
The other issue is that if the
language does need to be revisited,

01:08:26.940 --> 01:08:30.400
I think that's something
that we would be open to.

01:08:30.400 --> 01:08:33.680
But I don't think I've
seen any specific proposals

01:08:33.680 --> 01:08:35.460
about how that needs to be done.

01:08:35.460 --> 01:08:37.340
So that's something
that could be worked

01:08:37.340 --> 01:08:40.300
out before the next rulemaking
or during the next rulemaking.

01:08:40.300 --> 01:08:42.090
If we could come to consensus,

01:08:42.090 --> 01:08:45.110
we could address what the
changes are that need to be made.

01:08:45.110 --> 01:08:49.640
And again, if you put it in the
statute as it currently is drafted

01:08:49.640 --> 01:08:54.910
or in some new slightly revised
form, then that's how it will be.

01:08:54.910 --> 01:08:58.360
And the rulemaking, the benefit of
it is it's more flexible than that.

01:08:58.360 --> 01:08:59.710
You can revisit it.

01:08:59.710 --> 01:09:02.800
You can figure out, well, if
it's not fixing the problem,

01:09:02.800 --> 01:09:05.110
let's get together
and fix the problem.

01:09:05.110 --> 01:09:07.520
So that's I think the
better way to address it.

01:09:07.520 --> 01:09:08.820
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Although, I mean,

01:09:08.820 --> 01:09:13.600
a permanent exemption
wouldn't preclude, you know,

01:09:13.600 --> 01:09:16.480
future requests administratively.

01:09:16.480 --> 01:09:18.030
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: No,
I agree with that.

01:09:18.030 --> 01:09:21.620
But I also question
whether it makes sense to go

01:09:21.620 --> 01:09:23.570
through the whole legislative
process

01:09:23.570 --> 01:09:27.970
of putting new permanent
exemptions into the statute

01:09:27.970 --> 01:09:33.640
when it's unlikely they're going to
end up being the ultimate solution.

01:09:33.640 --> 01:09:37.580
And I think that's why Congress
created this rulemaking is

01:09:37.580 --> 01:09:40.570
that it knew there's going to
be a lot of things that come

01:09:40.570 --> 01:09:42.610
up that we can't address
in the statute.

01:09:42.610 --> 01:09:46.870
And so, you know, the Title
17 is very long already.

01:09:46.870 --> 01:09:49.390
And if we start putting
new things in it

01:09:49.390 --> 01:09:53.640
that very quickly become irrelevant
or become no longer capable

01:09:53.640 --> 01:09:57.530
of addressing the problems,
then I don't find--

01:09:57.530 --> 01:10:00.390
I don't think that that's a
helpful way to go about it.

01:10:00.390 --> 01:10:03.810
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: So, I hear you, but
Congress also implemented a variety

01:10:03.810 --> 01:10:06.780
of exceptions to the
prohibition on circumvention,

01:10:06.780 --> 01:10:08.320
which are these permanent
exemptions.

01:10:08.320 --> 01:10:10.720 position:56%
I mean, should we treat these on par

01:10:10.720 --> 01:10:12.850
with a continuously
renewed exemption or,

01:10:12.850 --> 01:10:14.150
you know, where is the line?

01:10:14.150 --> 01:10:18.090
Why have one for encryption but not
have one for assistive technology?

01:10:18.090 --> 01:10:19.390
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Sure.

01:10:19.390 --> 01:10:23.150
And I think you have to assess
every issue as it comes up.

01:10:23.150 --> 01:10:25.790
As I was saying earlier,
I think a lot

01:10:25.790 --> 01:10:32.660
of the permanent exemptions appear
to have largely done their job

01:10:32.660 --> 01:10:38.750
and that litigation is not taking
place that results in bad outcomes.

01:10:38.750 --> 01:10:42.380
And I think there's a lot of
people who seem to have concerns

01:10:42.380 --> 01:10:44.870 position:56%
about the scope of these exemptions.

01:10:44.870 --> 01:10:48.740
But there's not a lot of evidence
that if it actually got litigated,

01:10:48.740 --> 01:10:50.750
they wouldn't have
addressed the problem.

01:10:50.750 --> 01:10:54.730
But that being said, the fact
that no one is content with them

01:10:54.730 --> 01:10:59.600 position:56%
to me indicates that no matter how
we work through over the next couple

01:10:59.600 --> 01:11:03.070
of years creating new permanent
exemptions, someone's going

01:11:03.070 --> 01:11:04.730
to figure out a reason
why in a couple

01:11:04.730 --> 01:11:07.400
of years they're worried
they're not going to work right.

01:11:07.400 --> 01:11:10.370
And they're going to come
to you with those concerns.

01:11:10.370 --> 01:11:13.380
And so, I feel like that
renders the legislative work

01:11:13.380 --> 01:11:18.590
that everyone would have
to do a little more suspect

01:11:18.590 --> 01:11:22.400
because there's already a
process that, as I said yesterday,

01:11:22.400 --> 01:11:25.210
is working quite well
where the Office is able

01:11:25.210 --> 01:11:26.510
to address these things.

01:11:26.510 --> 01:11:30.510
And if you can get them renewed
in a much less burdensome fashion,

01:11:30.510 --> 01:11:36.090
that to me is far preferable to
going with the legislative route.

01:11:36.090 --> 01:11:37.390
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. Love?

01:11:37.390 --> 01:11:44.090 position:56%
&gt;&gt; James Love: I don't know if
you're aware of this, but we spent--

01:11:44.090 --> 01:11:47.160
I spent maybe five years of my
life working about half-time

01:11:47.160 --> 01:11:49.170
on this, you know, on this issue.

01:11:49.170 --> 01:11:53.010 position:56%
So we've followed the debates on it.

01:11:53.010 --> 01:11:57.110
I'd call attention to-- I
mean, if you look at the--

01:11:57.110 --> 01:11:59.860
certainly, the temporary thing
has been a problem for the groups.

01:11:59.860 --> 01:12:02.980
There's been years when almost
no evidence was provided

01:12:02.980 --> 01:12:05.750
for the renewal, just because it
was such a burdensome proceeding.

01:12:05.750 --> 01:12:08.940
And it would have been-- And
there was a recommendation

01:12:08.940 --> 01:12:11.040
by the professional staff
to get rid of the exception

01:12:11.040 --> 01:12:13.680
because the burden had been met
in the administrative proceeding.

01:12:13.680 --> 01:12:18.310 position:56%
But I think the Library of Congress
wisely extended the exception anyhow

01:12:18.310 --> 01:12:21.250
because it recognized that it was
just such a failure of the process

01:12:21.250 --> 01:12:23.570
and that the need was still there.

01:12:23.570 --> 01:12:27.110
So, I think the idea of having a
permanent exception is appealing,

01:12:27.110 --> 01:12:29.740
or at least a more durable
exception in some ways.

01:12:29.740 --> 01:12:35.870
The language in the treaty
that people have referred to,

01:12:35.870 --> 01:12:42.120
which says that the-- that you
shall take appropriate measures

01:12:42.120 --> 01:12:45.560
to make sure that beneficiary
persons can enjoy the limitations

01:12:45.560 --> 01:12:49.900
of the exceptions that they
should have, is kind of the level

01:12:49.900 --> 01:12:52.440
of generality where
maybe the specifics

01:12:52.440 --> 01:12:56.000
of how that's done could be
done more administratively.

01:12:56.000 --> 01:12:57.920
I'm sympathetic to the idea

01:12:57.920 --> 01:13:01.840
that rigid statutory
frameworks are not necessarily

01:13:01.840 --> 01:13:04.410
that appealing in a lot of cases.

01:13:04.410 --> 01:13:09.320
I know that there was an
earlier exception for the blind

01:13:09.320 --> 01:13:13.200
that had a commercial
availability provision in it.

01:13:13.200 --> 01:13:23.470
And there was a letter on the
21st of September, 2012 from NTIA

01:13:23.470 --> 01:13:29.350
to Maria Pallante that
discussed this issue.

01:13:29.350 --> 01:13:32.410
And some of this is I
think described in a note

01:13:32.410 --> 01:13:37.650
that Krista Cox is the
author of June 17th, 2013,

01:13:37.650 --> 01:13:42.560
Marrakesh note number four,
when Krista was working with us,

01:13:42.560 --> 01:13:44.320
was addressing this issue.

01:13:44.320 --> 01:13:45.940
And I would recommend that memo

01:13:45.940 --> 01:13:47.740
because I think it's
quite well-written

01:13:47.740 --> 01:13:51.290
and I think it's informative
on this point.

01:13:51.290 --> 01:13:55.400
But it's-- The finding by NTIA was

01:13:55.400 --> 01:13:58.350
that the interoperability problem
had gotten worse, not better.

01:13:58.350 --> 01:14:01.090
The hopes was-- We always hear
these talks, you're not going to--

01:14:01.090 --> 01:14:02.890
you know, licensing
will solve the problem,

01:14:02.890 --> 01:14:05.350
technology will solve the
problem, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:14:05.350 --> 01:14:09.560
But then, the thing that Krista
mentioned earlier about the cost

01:14:09.560 --> 01:14:13.110
of obtaining different devices--
also in the context of the treaty,

01:14:13.110 --> 01:14:16.820
you saw people making
these presentations

01:14:16.820 --> 01:14:18.710
in the treaty negotiations
that would get up

01:14:18.710 --> 01:14:22.100
and they would show you what
was considered to be accessible.

01:14:22.100 --> 01:14:27.360
Like one blind person from South
Africa, he had had a PDF reader.

01:14:27.360 --> 01:14:33.850
It would read an entire page
of text to him in the sort

01:14:33.850 --> 01:14:36.750
of permitted format that they
had accessibility where again,

01:14:36.750 --> 01:14:39.410
he was just trying to get the
footnote at the bottom of the page.

01:14:39.410 --> 01:14:41.950
And he'd try and copy it
down after he'd hear it.

01:14:41.950 --> 01:14:44.310
And then, he'd have to start it
again and again and he'd have

01:14:44.310 --> 01:14:45.860
to do it like several
different times

01:14:45.860 --> 01:14:49.340
because the reader he was using
didn't allow him to stop or cut

01:14:49.340 --> 01:14:51.020
and paste and things like that.

01:14:51.020 --> 01:14:53.970
Whereas other readers that people
were using were designed more

01:14:53.970 --> 01:14:56.280
functionality and were
really easier to use

01:14:56.280 --> 01:14:58.200
and more effective for people.

01:14:58.200 --> 01:15:02.010
Not only could you speed
up the process quite a bit,

01:15:02.010 --> 01:15:03.810
but you had other abilities to sort

01:15:03.810 --> 01:15:05.560
of utilize the text
in different ways.

01:15:05.560 --> 01:15:07.950
I think people that are not
really familiar with it--

01:15:07.950 --> 01:15:10.180
I wasn't that familiar with
it myself and I started

01:15:10.180 --> 01:15:11.480
to learn about these things.

01:15:11.480 --> 01:15:13.610
Just don't really understand
how high tech some

01:15:13.610 --> 01:15:16.910 position:56%
of the assistive technologies really
are and how idiosyncratic they are

01:15:16.910 --> 01:15:18.480
for the users and things like that.

01:15:18.480 --> 01:15:23.430
So, for that reason, NTIA
really changed its position

01:15:23.430 --> 01:15:24.730
on the commercial availability

01:15:24.730 --> 01:15:26.870
because they just didn't think it
was really a workable standard.

01:15:26.870 --> 01:15:31.900 position:56%
Now, that said, I think this balance
between having a permanent mandate

01:15:31.900 --> 01:15:34.730
to do something that makes
people unequal in the way

01:15:34.730 --> 01:15:37.160
that you're supposed to
is the right approach.

01:15:37.160 --> 01:15:41.740
And then, being able to
fine tune the details

01:15:41.740 --> 01:15:45.640
of how the exception is implemented
over time, probably a good idea.

01:15:45.640 --> 01:15:46.940
My mother's deaf.

01:15:46.940 --> 01:15:50.160
She was one of the people who was
excluded from the Marrakesh Treaty

01:15:50.160 --> 01:15:52.110
because the motion
picture industry insisted

01:15:52.110 --> 01:15:54.080
on that in the negotiations.

01:15:54.080 --> 01:15:58.540 position:56%
Her situation's better today than it
was in the old days because we used

01:15:58.540 --> 01:16:01.320
to have to buy separate
devices to do kind of captioning

01:16:01.320 --> 01:16:02.700
and now you can get that more--

01:16:02.700 --> 01:16:06.660
even Netflix has it these
days, which is kind of nice.

01:16:06.660 --> 01:16:10.170
But it is the case that it
was I think a disappointment

01:16:10.170 --> 01:16:13.970
that the Marrakesh Treaty on
print disabilities was as narrow.

01:16:13.970 --> 01:16:15.630
It was a political decision.

01:16:15.630 --> 01:16:18.220
But it also permitted countries
to implement them more widely.

01:16:18.220 --> 01:16:20.550
And I think US law is
wider in a lot of areas,

01:16:20.550 --> 01:16:21.890
certainly in the area of education.

01:16:21.890 --> 01:16:27.160
So I think that striking the right
balance as to how inclusive it is,

01:16:27.160 --> 01:16:30.720
but also recognizing that maybe
the exceptions are maybe better

01:16:30.720 --> 01:16:34.350
understood in some areas
of disabilities in terms

01:16:34.350 --> 01:16:38.290
of the overall effect on all the
stakeholders is probably accurate

01:16:38.290 --> 01:16:39.930
as well.

01:16:39.930 --> 01:16:44.480
So, you know, I think maybe--

01:16:44.480 --> 01:16:46.290
sort of arguing against
myself a little bit--

01:16:46.290 --> 01:16:48.220
like sort of maybe sort of
giving like kind of like--

01:16:48.220 --> 01:16:52.140
accepting that you sort of know
what you're doing in some areas

01:16:52.140 --> 01:16:54.040
and you know you should be
doing something in other areas,

01:16:54.040 --> 01:16:55.730
but maybe you're not quite
as confident you know what

01:16:55.730 --> 01:16:59.790
that thing is just yet
is probably realistic.

01:16:59.790 --> 01:17:01.090
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

01:17:01.090 --> 01:17:02.950
I think we're going
to go to Ms. Koberidze

01:17:02.950 --> 01:17:06.360
and then back to Mr. Cazares.

01:17:06.360 --> 01:17:09.000
&gt;&gt; Maryna Koberidze: I believe
there is a strong support

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:12.310
for a permanent exemption
for print-disabled people.

01:17:12.310 --> 01:17:16.960
And we have rulemaking
records since 2003.

01:17:16.960 --> 01:17:21.330
We have case law, Authors
Guild v. HathiTrust.

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:26.660
We have Chafee amendment and we
have also international obligations

01:17:26.660 --> 01:17:28.190
under Marrakesh Treaty.

01:17:28.190 --> 01:17:37.230
And although despite
all these regulations,

01:17:37.230 --> 01:17:44.530
print-disabled people still
cannot benefit from the exemptions

01:17:44.530 --> 01:17:47.530
that are granted within
the rulemaking proceedings.

01:17:47.530 --> 01:17:52.030
And this is because
they need accessibility

01:17:52.030 --> 01:17:53.930
and they need third
party assistance.

01:17:53.930 --> 01:17:57.360
And I think it would
be very important

01:17:57.360 --> 01:18:03.940 position:56%
when we consider permanent exemption
to consider these two issues,

01:18:03.940 --> 01:18:06.960
how to facilitate accessibility
and how

01:18:06.960 --> 01:18:09.510
to facilitate third
party assistance.

01:18:09.510 --> 01:18:12.600
Whether it will be through
mediation process, as I mentioned,

01:18:12.600 --> 01:18:15.980
with the copyright holders
or whether it will be

01:18:15.980 --> 01:18:18.240
with help of the Copyright Office.

01:18:18.240 --> 01:18:21.370
Or maybe, there could
be a third solution

01:18:21.370 --> 01:18:25.180
to create a separate
management organization similar

01:18:25.180 --> 01:18:28.150
to Sound Exchange in the
music industry which will help

01:18:28.150 --> 01:18:31.710
to manage third party
assistance issues.

01:18:31.710 --> 01:18:33.240
Thank you.

01:18:33.240 --> 01:18:34.670
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you very much.

01:18:34.670 --> 01:18:35.970
Mr. Cazares?

01:18:35.970 --> 01:18:38.400
&gt;&gt; Gabe Cazares: I
think that a couple

01:18:38.400 --> 01:18:39.720
of great points have been made.

01:18:39.720 --> 01:18:43.540
I agree in part with Mr. Williams.

01:18:43.540 --> 01:18:50.800
I think that the forthcoming of
EPUB-3 and HTML-5 are going to kind

01:18:50.800 --> 01:18:55.030
of revolutionize the way
accessibility is approached

01:18:55.030 --> 01:18:56.330
in the mainstream.

01:18:56.330 --> 01:18:59.610
But I also want to address the
fact of the permanent exemption.

01:18:59.610 --> 01:19:06.130
The fact is that people with
disabilities, particularly the AFB,

01:19:06.130 --> 01:19:07.610
the American Foundation
for the Blind

01:19:07.610 --> 01:19:12.730 position:56%
and other folks have been requesting
exemptions that have been,

01:19:12.730 --> 01:19:17.850
by and large, being renewed
with little to no opposition

01:19:17.850 --> 01:19:20.370
because the circumstances
really don't change

01:19:20.370 --> 01:19:22.060
for people with disabilities.

01:19:22.060 --> 01:19:27.500
I think given the notion-- the
fact that we have a large number

01:19:27.500 --> 01:19:29.480
of people who are blind
or visually impaired

01:19:29.480 --> 01:19:33.350
in this country alone
guarantees a permanent exemption.

01:19:33.350 --> 01:19:36.880
I don't see the need, until
the process is reformed,

01:19:36.880 --> 01:19:42.400
for the renewal-- the
rulemaking process,

01:19:42.400 --> 01:19:47.120
I don't see the reason why
people with disabilities,

01:19:47.120 --> 01:19:51.700 position:56%
people who are print-disabled have
to go through the burdensome process

01:19:51.700 --> 01:19:54.820
of requesting for and waiting

01:19:54.820 --> 01:19:58.410
to be granted another
three-year exemption.

01:19:58.410 --> 01:20:02.510
I think that this particular
circumstance, given the situation

01:20:02.510 --> 01:20:06.870
of blind and print-disabled
Americans,

01:20:06.870 --> 01:20:09.990
warrants a permanent exemption.

01:20:11.110 --> 01:20:12.410
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you very much.

01:20:12.410 --> 01:20:16.740
I think we have quite
broad agreement

01:20:16.740 --> 01:20:19.390 position:56%
on that topic, which is encouraging.

01:20:19.390 --> 01:20:24.360
We have-- We're getting
close to the end.

01:20:24.360 --> 01:20:29.750
And so, I think we just had
one or two sort of suggestions

01:20:29.750 --> 01:20:32.700
for permanent exemptions that we
wanted to ask your views about.

01:20:32.700 --> 01:20:37.490
One proposal that came
up in the comments was

01:20:37.490 --> 01:20:41.270
to make the current
unlocking exemption permanent.

01:20:41.270 --> 01:20:46.970
We'd be interested in your views
on the advisability of that.

01:20:51.980 --> 01:20:53.900
Mr. Dow?

01:20:53.900 --> 01:20:57.970
&gt;&gt; Troy Dow: So, I think it was
Mr. Adler in the previous panel

01:20:57.970 --> 01:21:02.100
who read some from the legislative
history and the contextual part

01:21:02.100 --> 01:21:05.100 position:56%
of the unlocking-- the circumstances
of the unlocking legislation.

01:21:05.100 --> 01:21:07.570
And I think that that
counsels towards an approach

01:21:07.570 --> 01:21:10.510
that says a permanent
exception for that type

01:21:10.510 --> 01:21:12.540
of thing is really
not the way to go.

01:21:12.540 --> 01:21:15.290
And I think that's not
unique to unlocking per se.

01:21:15.290 --> 01:21:16.700
I think that really
applies when you're dealing

01:21:16.700 --> 01:21:20.450
with very technologically
specific items in general.

01:21:20.450 --> 01:21:25.430
But the one thing on the unlocking
legislation specifically was

01:21:25.430 --> 01:21:26.940
that the unique circumstances
of that was

01:21:26.940 --> 01:21:28.810
that we knew what that meant.

01:21:28.810 --> 01:21:30.450
We knew what it meant
to unlock a phone.

01:21:30.450 --> 01:21:32.660
We knew that what it meant was
the entry of a code, right?

01:21:32.660 --> 01:21:35.220
It was a handful of digits
that could be entered in.

01:21:35.220 --> 01:21:37.800
And the only thing that resulted
from the entry of those digits was

01:21:37.800 --> 01:21:40.100
that you could connect
that phone to a network.

01:21:40.100 --> 01:21:41.780
It didn't expose the
content on the phone.

01:21:41.780 --> 01:21:43.280
It didn't expose personal
information.

01:21:43.280 --> 01:21:44.810
There weren't privacy
interests that were affected.

01:21:44.810 --> 01:21:46.110
There weren't copyright interests.

01:21:46.110 --> 01:21:48.380
It was a very narrow thing.

01:21:48.380 --> 01:21:50.010
But we didn't know what
that was going to mean

01:21:50.010 --> 01:21:51.490
for the next device, right?

01:21:51.490 --> 01:21:53.440
I mean, that was one of the
issues that we talked about,

01:21:53.440 --> 01:21:55.740
should this be expanded
into the context of tablets

01:21:55.740 --> 01:21:57.820
and other computing devices, right?

01:21:57.820 --> 01:21:59.920
Does circumvention for the purposes

01:21:59.920 --> 01:22:02.380
of connecting the device mean
the same thing in those contexts?

01:22:02.380 --> 01:22:04.830
Does it mean simply that you can
connect that device to a network

01:22:04.830 --> 01:22:06.810
or does it mean that all of a
sudden, it does implicate some

01:22:06.810 --> 01:22:10.200
of these other interests
that didn't exist at the time

01:22:10.200 --> 01:22:11.770
of the cell phone unlocking
legislation?

01:22:11.770 --> 01:22:15.790 position:56%
And so, I think the legislative
history speaks specifically to that.

01:22:15.790 --> 01:22:17.760
It talks about that being
a unique circumstance

01:22:17.760 --> 01:22:20.090
and why Congress was
comfortable doing it.

01:22:20.090 --> 01:22:24.210
And I think it speaks towards why,
in the context of trying to look

01:22:24.210 --> 01:22:26.520
at that for other devices
and in other contexts,

01:22:26.520 --> 01:22:31.100
it really requires a specific focus
and one that's uniquely suited

01:22:31.100 --> 01:22:34.310
to something like the rulemaking as
opposed to the legislative process

01:22:34.310 --> 01:22:37.210
and the permanent exemption.

