01:51:12.430 --> 01:51:15.800 position:56%
And most of the folks making those--
taking those positions are the folks

01:51:15.800 --> 01:51:17.100
on the rights holders' side.

01:51:17.100 --> 01:51:18.710
And I think it's important
to realize,

01:51:18.710 --> 01:51:20.620
as Professor Tushnet
put it yesterday,

01:51:20.620 --> 01:51:23.080
that there are asymmetries
in the process.

01:51:23.080 --> 01:51:28.130
That if the process is falling
short of its goal, for example,

01:51:28.130 --> 01:51:32.000
of providing the exemptions that
are necessary to the public,

01:51:32.000 --> 01:51:35.670
that leaves the rights holders,
you know, whole in a sense,

01:51:35.670 --> 01:51:38.400
that the ban is working,
the 1201(a) prohibition

01:51:38.400 --> 01:51:40.590
on circumvention is still working.

01:51:40.590 --> 01:51:42.420
You know, the process only
isn't working for them

01:51:42.420 --> 01:51:44.860
when the exemptions go too far.

01:51:44.860 --> 01:51:49.600
And I think it's worth sort
of noting that because,

01:51:49.600 --> 01:51:51.070
especially I think the discussion

01:51:51.070 --> 01:51:54.600
about the renewability being
academic, I think is important

01:51:54.600 --> 01:51:56.000
to realize because
there have been cases

01:51:56.000 --> 01:51:58.940
where exemptions haven't
been renewed.

01:51:58.940 --> 01:52:01.580
And I think for those on the
proponent side, it's not academic

01:52:01.580 --> 01:52:03.870
that there is a risk of
exemption not being granted,

01:52:03.870 --> 01:52:05.410
that the burden is on them

01:52:05.410 --> 01:52:07.740
to provide the proof
necessary to get the exemption.

01:52:07.740 --> 01:52:09.960
So I don't think that's
an academic discussion.

01:52:09.960 --> 01:52:11.910
And finally, on that
point, and especially tying

01:52:11.910 --> 01:52:14.600
into the accessibility discussion,
the example that Mr. Love brought

01:52:14.600 --> 01:52:17.120
up of footnotes not
being accessible.

01:52:17.120 --> 01:52:19.300
That might be a case where
someone might say, well,

01:52:19.300 --> 01:52:21.250
95% of literature is accessible.

01:52:21.250 --> 01:52:22.550
That's just an edge case.

01:52:22.550 --> 01:52:26.170
When you're the user and that
particular case implicates you,

01:52:26.170 --> 01:52:27.470
it's not an edge case.

01:52:27.470 --> 01:52:29.000
That is a failure of the system.

01:52:29.000 --> 01:52:32.340
And I think the exemption
process and the user carve-outs

01:52:32.340 --> 01:52:34.300
in the permanent exemptions
aren't meant

01:52:34.300 --> 01:52:36.120
to cover those edge
cases in particular.

01:52:36.120 --> 01:52:38.560
So I would urge the
Office to consider in terms

01:52:38.560 --> 01:52:41.910
of evaluating what the burden of
proof should be, is considering

01:52:41.910 --> 01:52:45.440
that edge cases don't necessarily
mean the system is working.

01:52:45.440 --> 01:52:47.570
Thank you.

